[13:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'click button 25 and it gets a new transcription of the page, it gets information about what has changed. We can probably see it here. Yeah, this is how the agent operates, right? 19 tokens just telling me opening self update now'

[13:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'space browser click browser number one button number 47. That\'s it. And it gets response like this and &gt;&gt; this or was it also another auto research? &gt;&gt; Well, partly both. Partly both but I did this mostly myself. So I found a'

[13:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'library on the internet that transcribes HTML into markdown and I edited it heavily with the help of AI to produce this format where every interactive element gets reference number while text'

[14:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'text just stays text. And then we kept iterating and we had to do a lot of optimizations and solve a lot of edge cases because it might not seem like a difficult technology the web but'

[14:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'websites are super hard to crawl. You have so many different elements nested like iframes and shadow DOMs, things that are like naturally closed. Some of them the shadow DOM is built for the sole purpose'

[14:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of like prevent scraping. So we even had to inject some hacks into the browser render itself so that it automatically opens everything on the website so it\'s scrapable. So yeah, it was a lot of'

[14:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work. Partly AI, partly me but in the end it works like a charm. And as you can see we are now at 13.6 thousand tokens. So we only added what like two more thousand tokens?'

[14:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; All the two thousand. &gt;&gt; Yeah, since since the beginning four but previously we did something with the space and that is because another thing we use, we don\'t keep we don\'t keep things like this in the history because like once the state of the page is gone'

[15:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the past then we don\'t need it anymore. &gt;&gt; Yeah. &gt;&gt; Yeah, it could be confusing and it it would eat up a lot of tokens, right? It\'s what is it like 2000 tokens. And that\'s why we use this transient space,'

[15:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that means the context that changes often, we always put it to the very end of the prompt after the last caching breakpoint, so it doesn\'t get cached and it can be replaced on every turn of the'

[15:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'conversation. So, when the agent is editing widgets, we always load the last state of the source code of the widget and we put it to the transient. So, the agent can always see the source code of the widget it works with, but it doesn\'t stay in the history consuming tokens'

[15:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with every other turn because this is exactly what compounds, right? It\'s not a problem if you like load 2,000 tokens to show the agent the page, but if you keep it in the history, you have added 2,000 tokens forever. And if the agent'

[15:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clicks like five pages, you have added 10,000 tokens to every turn of the conversation. &gt;&gt; Yeah. &gt;&gt; And if you start removing, then you break caching. So, that\'s another problem. If you touch something &gt;&gt; Yeah, if you touch something in the'

[16:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'history, you invalidate the cache and you start paying more again. So, this way we keep the prices of we keep the token spending as low as possible and maintain the best efficiency and long-lasting contact windows.'

